    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>INVESTMENT DROUGHT IN VIETNAM</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Wayne Arnold</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Arnold, Wayne</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Vietnam approved $440.5 million in foreign investments during first seven months of year, 44 percent drop from 1999 period (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Illustrating how foreign companies have soured on Vietnam, its state-run media reported that the country had approved $440.5 million in foreign investment in the first seven months of this year, a 44 percent drop from a year earlier. Last month, Vietnam signed a trade agreement with the United States that commits it to gradual changes that many hope will reverse the trend. But the International Monetary Fund has called for more urgent change: allowing unprofitable state-owned enterprises to fail, easing capital controls and strengthening banks.</p>
        <p>Wayne Arnold</p>
      </block>
